% spi_quad.nw -- 4-lane QUADSPI sustained wall-rate validation.
%
% Lives as a sibling chapter to src/spi.nw. The parent Makefile auto-
% discovers it via CHAPTERS := $(notdir $(basename $(wildcard src/*.nw)))
% and applies CHAP_RULES so a build/spi_quad/ tree is created without
% any parent-Makefile changes.

== Quad-lane wall-rate chapter

This chapter scopes the 4-lane (LANES=4) QUADSPI sweep tests so the
mission-critical wall-rate measurement runs in isolation from the
1-lane regression in `src/spi.nw`. The mission target is sustained
FPGA->MP135 transfer of at least 200 Mbps in quad mode with no data
errors. The bitstream is `qspi.bin`, built by the spi/qspi chapters as
a side effect of `make -C build/spi bitstreams`; no new RTL is
introduced here.

Iter 7 strategy reset: prior iterations chased HDL flop deltas in
qspi.nw to fix sporadic 0x6B byte alignment, only to discover that
synthesis/P&R margin sensitivity made HDL chasing untenable (every
HDL change regressed at least one of the 0x6C/0x6D/0x6E/0x6F
diagnostics even with single-flop deltas). The spi_1lane_stream
chapter proved 107 Mbps over 32 MiB at presc=5 sshift=1 using the
auto-consume `A` command path (cli.c:1236, cmd_auto_stream ->
stream_direct_crc_eligible -> stream_direct_crc_read ->
qspi_mdma_crc_read at qspi.c:790). That path uses hardware MDMA +
hardware CRC1 drain through DMA, while `b` (cmd_bench) uses
CPU-polled FIFO byte-by-byte and tops out at ~10-20 Mbps. We switch
this chapter to the same `A` path used by spi_1lane_stream while
keeping the four 0x6C/0x6D/0x6E/0x6F nibble diagnostics unchanged.

The chapter tests three prescaler settings on the auto-stream path:
`presc=203` (~3.09 MHz SCLK x 4 lanes ~12.4 Mbps) as a baseline,
`presc=63` (~10.25 MHz x 4 ~41 Mbps) as a medium-rate sanity check,
and `presc=5` (~109.3 MHz x 4 ~437 Mbps physical maximum) as the
mission-critical wall-rate target. The presc=5 block enforces the
>=200 Mbps wall-rate floor; the other two blocks enforce only pattern
correctness so the regression has clean low-rate evidence even if
the high-rate path margin-fails.

Presc=15 (~21 MHz SCLK) is intentionally skipped. It is the SB_IO
output-flop timing-margin failure documented in the spi block 8
BLOCKED record in `agent4/TODO.md`: at the 1-lane bench it produced
non-deterministic CRC corruption and DLYB engagement at the midrange
tap converted the failure into a transfer hang. The 4-lane variant
samples the same FPGA SB_IO outputs at the same kernel frequency, so
including it here would risk the same margin failure aborting the
sweep before the higher-rate presc=5 block gets a chance to run. The
mission target is reachable from presc=5 alone, so the skip costs no
mission progress.

A preflight smoke block (`A 1024 1 0`) runs first to prove the
`qspi.bin` bitstream is loaded and that the 4-lane data-phase reaches
the MP135 with the expected incrementing byte pattern via the
auto-stream path. If the preflight fails, the bench blocks would all
fail with the same root cause, so spending 1 block on the cheaper
smoke test isolates the diagnosis quickly.

CRITICAL gotcha: `A LEN 1 1` (quad raw=1) does NOT WORK. The slave's
`quad_start` is gated on `opcode==0x6B/6C/...`; with raw=1 the master
skips the opcode byte, the slave's opcode register stays 0, and
quad_start never fires. Always use `A LEN 1 0` for quad (raw=0 means
the master sends opcode 0x6B + 8 dummy cycles, then 4-lane data
phase).

<<TEST.md>>=
Cycle 2 iter 77 plan: validate quad raw streaming with TWIN-PASS
reproducibility on real varying data. The slave is `spi_quad.bin`
(LANES=4 from spi.nw, byte-incrementing pattern across all bytes).
The firmware's `A LEN 1 1` quad raw path now does TWO sequential
direct-CRC reads of LEN bytes each and reports `firsterr=-1` only
when both hardware-CRC32 results are equal AND non-trivial -- this
proves the channel transports the same varying byte stream
identically twice. Wall rate is computed from the FIRST pass alone
(via the `stream_xfer LEN B quad` sentinel that fires between the
two passes).

Phase A -- diagnostic: at presc=63 (slow) run `m 256 1 1`
(MDMA-into-DDR raw quad) twice so the captured UART contains two
firsterr_dump lines we can compare for byte-exact reproducibility.
The firmware also prints the legacy `mdma N B quad ...` summary
with `firsterr=<offset>` (computed against (i & 0xFF)) -- we use
this to see whether the MDMA path produces the canonical
incrementing pattern.

```
fpga.hx1k:program bin=@spi_quad.bin
bench_mcu:reset_dut  # blobs: @main.stm32 (referenced from flash.tsv)
delay ms=2500
dfu.evb:flash_layout layout=@flash.tsv no_reconnect=true
mp135.evb:uart_open
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel="JEDEC ID:" timeout_ms=10000
delay ms=300
mp135.evb:uart_write data="p 63\r"
delay ms=100
mp135.evb:uart_write data="o 256\r"
delay ms=200
mp135.evb:uart_write data="m 256 1 1\r"
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel="mdma 256 B quad" timeout_ms=10000
delay ms=300
mp135.evb:uart_write data="o 256\r"
delay ms=200
mp135.evb:uart_write data="m 256 1 1\r"
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel="mdma 256 B quad" timeout_ms=10000
mp135.evb:uart_close
```

- Check Phase A diagnostic mdma quad raw at presc=63

Phase A1 -- single-chunk twin-DDR diagnostic at presc=63. Iter 77
v1 found that the direct-CRC twin-pass at 16 MiB also gave
different CRCs across passes (`ec75b686` vs `8dee8d8d`) even
though the 256 B `m` MDMA was REPRODUCIBLE. The CRC1 path
finishes the QSPI transaction differently from the DDR-MDMA
path (no_inval + abort vs. full TCF wait + invalidate) and the
slave's first-sample alignment is non-deterministic across two
direct-CRC invocations. Use the new `T <len>` command instead --
it does TWO `qspi_mdma_read` (DDR-MDMA, same path as the
PROVEN-REPRODUCIBLE 256 B `m` test) into two 16 MiB DDR slots
and byte-compares them. This bypasses the CRC1 path entirely.

```
